text: All by, I think, multi-factor kind of strategy, probably between 60-40 asset allocation. I think the thing for me is that if you believe U.S., the beacon of the hill, if people can come together and solve the problems, then there are still great potentials that we could make some productivity breakthrough. If you look at the longer economic, the real economic growth has been 1.8%, 2% in the last couple hundred years. If we can just make a little bit closer to that, instead of the 1.4% productive growth, if people are more productive, you still believe U.S. should have confidence as a country, the political, the economic, then you will think equity will still deliver value. Of course, I would like to have. Some fixed income exposure just to against low risk. I think if I were much richer, I'll go for 100% equity, but I'm not. So, and I still believe if you believe multi-factor is based on human behavior and humans still live, then humans is going to still have all these faults or these constraints. We only live certain 24 hours. Time is limited. So if you consider this, then a multi-factor should deliver value. So I think that is easy. But of course that is my, because I'm constrained, but if you are very rich, they could invest in a new technology could really change the trajectory. I think that a lot of those grand things that you can, but given my limited investment and my responsibility to my kids, I think a multi-factor boasting equity and bond portfolio in the public equity market probably suits me the best.
